# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: goal-oriented-action-planning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Artificial intelligence (AI) in video games refers to the computational systems that control non-player characters (NPCs), generate dynamic game behavior, or simulate strategic decision-making.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In practice, the term covers a broad range of techniques drawn from computer science, control theory, and robotics rather than "true" artificial intelligence.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Moreover, academic AI—aimed at developing autonomous reasoning or learning—is distinct from game AI, whose goal is to deliver engaging, believable, and efficient behavior for players.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The term *CPU* in video games refer to the AI that control a NPC that could be a playable character in some other situations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In general, game AI does not, as might be thought and sometimes is depicted to be the case, mean a realization of an artificial person corresponding to an NPC in the manner of the Turing test or an artificial general intelligence.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some commentators in the video game industry have claimed that advances in game AI have transformed how players interact with digital systems more broadly.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Marketing discussions sometimes attribute human-like traits to game AI—such as personality or creative autonomy—but these are often scripted behaviors designed to mimic complexity rather than emergent cognition.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game playing was an area of research in AI from its inception.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the first examples of AI is the computerized game of Nim made in 1941 and published in 1942.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite being advanced technology in the year it was made, 20 years before *Pong*, the game took the form of a relatively small box and was able to regularly win games even against highly skilled players of the game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 1951, using the Ferranti Mark 1 machine of the University of Manchester, Christopher Strachey wrote a checkers program and Dietrich Prinz wrote one for chess.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These were among the first computer programs ever written.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Arthur Samuel's checkers program, developed in the middle 1950s and early 1960s, eventually achieved sufficient skill to challenge a respectable amateur.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Work on checkers and chess would culminate in the defeat of Garry Kasparov by IBM's Deep Blue computer in 1997.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first video games developed in the 1960s and early 1970s, like *Spacewar!*, *Pong*, and *Gotcha* (1973), were games implemented on discrete logic and strictly based on the competition of two players, without AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games that featured a single player mode with enemies started appearing in the 1970s.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first notable ones for the arcade appeared in 1974: the Taito game *Speed Race* (racing video game) and the Atari games *Qwak* (duck hunting light gun shooter) and *Pursuit* (fighter aircraft dogfighting simulator).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Two text-based computer games, *Star Trek* (1971) and *Hunt the Wumpus* (1973), also had enemies.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemy movement was based on stored patterns.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The incorporation of microprocessors would allow more computation and random elements overlaid into movement patterns.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Galaxian* (1979) added more complex and varied enemy movements, including maneuvers by individual enemies who break out of formation.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Pac-Man* (1980) introduced AI patterns to maze games, with the added quirk of different personalities for each enemy.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Karate Champ* (1984) later introduced AI patterns to fighting games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *First Queen* (1988) was a tactical action RPG which featured characters that can be controlled by the computer's AI in following the leader.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The role-playing video game *Dragon Quest IV* (1990) introduced a "Tactics" system, where the user can adjust the AI routines of non-player characters during battle, a concept later introduced to the action role-playing game genre by *Secret of Mana* (1993).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games like *Madden Football*, *Earl Weaver Baseball* and *Tony La Russa Baseball* all based their AI in an attempt to duplicate on the computer the coaching or managerial style of the selected celebrity.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Madden, Weaver and La Russa all did extensive work with these game development teams to maximize the accuracy of the games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later sports titles allowed users to "tune" variables in the AI to produce a player-defined managerial or coaching strategy.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The emergence of new game genres in the 1990s prompted the use of formal AI tools like finite-state machines.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Real-time strategy games taxed the AI with many objects, incomplete information, pathfinding problems, real-time decisions and economic planning, among other things.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first games of the genre had notorious problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Herzog Zwei* (1989), for example, had almost broken pathfinding and very basic three-state state machines for unit control, and *Dune II* (1992) attacked the players' base in a beeline and used numerous cheats.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games in the genre exhibited more sophisticated AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games have used bottom-up AI methods, such as the emergent behaviour and evaluation of player actions in games like *Creatures* or *Black & White*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Façade* was released in 2005 and used interactive multiple way dialogs and AI as the main aspect of game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games have provided an environment for developing artificial intelligence with potential applications beyond gameplay.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Examples include Watson, a Jeopardy!-playing computer; and the RoboCup tournament, where robots are trained to compete in soccer.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many experts complain that the "AI" in the term *game AI* overstates its worth, as game AI is not about intelligence, and shares few of the objectives of the academic field of AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Whereas "real AI" addresses fields of machine learning, decision making based on arbitrary data input, and even the ultimate goal of strong AI that can reason, "game AI" often consists of a half-dozen rules of thumb, or heuristics, that are just enough to give a good gameplay experience.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Historically, academic game-AI projects have been relatively separate from commercial products because the academic approaches tended to be simple and non-scalable.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial game AI has developed its own set of tools, which have been sufficient to give good performance in many cases.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game developers' increasing awareness of academic AI and a growing interest in computer games by the academic community is causing the definition of what counts as AI in a game to become less idiosyncratic.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Nevertheless, significant differences between different application domains of AI mean that game AI can still be viewed as a distinct subfield of AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In particular, the ability to legitimately solve some AI problems in games by cheating creates an important distinction.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, inferring the position of an unseen object from past observations can be a difficult problem when AI is applied to robotics, but in a computer game a NPC can simply look up the position in the game's scene graph.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Such cheating can lead to unrealistic behavior and so is not always desirable.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] But its possibility serves to distinguish game AI and leads to new problems to solve, such as when and how to cheat.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The major limitation to strong AI is the inherent depth of thinking and the extreme complexity of the decision-making process.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This means that although it would be then theoretically possible to make "smart" AI the problem would take considerable processing power.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI/heuristic algorithms are used in a wide variety of quite disparate fields inside a game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The most obvious is in the control of any NPCs in the game, although "scripting" (decision tree) is currently the most common means of control.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These handwritten decision trees often result in "artificial stupidity" such as repetitive behavior, loss of immersion, or abnormal behavior in situations the developers did not plan for.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding, another common use for AI, is widely seen in real-time strategy games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding is the method for determining how to get a NPC from one point on a map to another, taking into consideration the terrain, obstacles and possibly "fog of war".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial videogames often use fast and simple "grid-based pathfinding", wherein the terrain is mapped onto a rigid grid of uniform squares and a pathfinding algorithm such as A* or IDA* is applied to the grid.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Instead of just a rigid grid, some games use irregular polygons and assemble a navigation mesh out of the areas of the map that NPCs can walk to.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As a third method, it is sometimes convenient for developers to manually select "waypoints" that NPCs should use to navigate; the cost is that such waypoints can create unnatural-looking movement.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, waypoints tend to perform worse than navigation meshes in complex environments.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Beyond static pathfinding, navigation is a sub-field of Game AI focusing on giving NPCs the capability to navigate in a dynamic environment, finding a path to a target while avoiding collisions with other entities (other NPC, players...) or collaborating with them (group navigation).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Navigation in dynamic strategy games with large numbers of units, such as Age of Empires (1997) or Civilization V (2010), often performs poorly; units often get in the way of other units.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than improve the Game AI to properly solve a difficult problem in the virtual environment, it is often more cost-effective to just modify the scenario to be more tractable.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If pathfinding gets bogged down over a specific obstacle, a developer may just end up moving or deleting the obstacle.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many contemporary video games fall under the category of action, first-person shooter, or adventure.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In most of these types of games, there is some level of combat that takes place.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI's ability to be efficient in combat is important in these genres.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A common goal today is to make the AI more human or at least appear so.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the more positive and efficient features found in modern-day video game AI is the ability to hunt.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI originally reacted in a very black and white manner.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the player were in a specific area then the AI would react in either a complete offensive manner or be entirely defensive.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In recent years, the idea of "hunting" has been introduced; in this 'hunting' state the AI will look for realistic markers, such as sounds made by the character or footprints they may have left behind.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These developments ultimately allow for a more complex form of play.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With this feature, the player can actually consider how to approach or avoid an enemy.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is a feature that is particularly prevalent in the stealth genre.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another development in recent game AI has been the development of "survival instinct".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In-game computers can recognize different objects in an environment and determine whether it is beneficial or detrimental to its survival.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Like a user, the AI can look for cover in a firefight before taking actions that would leave it otherwise vulnerable, such as reloading a weapon or throwing a grenade.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] There can be set markers that tell it when to react in a certain way.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the AI is given a command to check its health throughout a game then further commands can be set so that it reacts a specific way at a certain percentage of health.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the health is below a certain threshold then the AI can be set to run away from the player and avoid it until another function is triggered.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another example could be if the AI notices it is out of bullets, it will find a cover object and hide behind it until it has reloaded.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Actions like these make the AI seem more human.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there is still a need for improvement in this area.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another side-effect of combat AI occurs when two AI-controlled characters encounter each other; first popularized in the id Software game *Doom*, so-called 'monster infighting' can break out in certain situations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Specifically, AI agents that are programmed to respond to hostile attacks will sometimes attack *each other* if their cohort's attacks land too close to them.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the case of *Doom*, published gameplay manuals even suggest taking advantage of monster infighting in order to survive certain levels and difficulty settings.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural content generation (PCG) is an AI technique to autonomously create ingame content through algorithms with minimal input from designers.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG is typically used to dynamically generate game features such as levels, NPC dialogue, and sounds.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers input specific parameters to guide the algorithms into making content for them.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG offers numerous advantages from both a developmental and player experience standpoint.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game studios are able to spend less money on artists and save time on production.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are given a fresh, highly replayable experience as the game generates new content each time they play.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG allows game content to adapt in real time to the player's actions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative algorithms (a rudimentary form of AI) have been used for level creation for decades.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The iconic 1980 dungeon crawler computer game *Rogue* is a foundational example.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are tasked with descending through the increasingly difficult levels of a dungeon to retrieve the Amulet of Yendor.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The dungeon levels are algorithmically generated at the start of each game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The save file is deleted every time the player dies.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithmic dungeon generation creates unique gameplay that would not otherwise be there as the goal of retrieving the amulet is the same each time.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The roguelike video game genre, derived from *Rogue*, feature games that use some type of procedural generation to provide near infinite replayability.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Opinions on total level generation as seen in games like *Rogue* can vary.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some developers can be skeptical of the quality of generated content and desire to create a world with a more "human" feel so they will use PCG more sparingly.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Consequently, they will only use PCG to generate specific components of an otherwise handcrafted level.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A notable example of this is Ubisoft's 2017 tactical shooter *Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers used a pathfinding algorithm trained with a data set of real maps to create road networks that would weave through handcrafted villages within the game world.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is an intelligent use of PCG as the AI would have a large amount of real world data to work with and roads are straightforward to create.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, the AI would likely miss nuances and subtleties if it was tasked with creating a village where people live.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As AI has become more advanced, developer goals are shifting to create massive repositories of levels from data sets.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2023, researchers from New York University and the University of the Witwatersrand trained a large language model to generate levels in the style of the 1981 puzzle game *Sokoban*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They found that the model excelled at generating levels with specifically requested characteristics such as difficulty level or layout.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, current models such as the one used in the study require large datasets of levels to be effective.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They concluded that, while promising, the high data cost of large language models currently outweighs the benefits for this application.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Continued advancements in the field will likely lead to more mainstream use in the future.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The musical score of a video game is an important expression of the emotional tone of a scene to the player.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sound effects such as the noise of a weapon hitting an enemy help indicate the effect of the player's actions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generating these in real time creates an engaging experience for the player because the game is more responsive to their input.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] An example is the 2013 adventure game *Proteus* where an algorithm dynamically adapts the music based on the angle the player is viewing the ingame landscape from.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent breakthroughs in AI have resulted in the creation of advanced tools that are capable of creating music and sound based on evolving factors with minimal developer input.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such example is the MetaComposure music generator.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] MetaComposure is an evolutionary algorithm designed to generate original music compositions during real time gameplay to match the current mood of the environment.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithm is able to assess the current mood of the game state through "mood tagging".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Research indicates that there is a significant positive statistical correlation regarding player rated game engagement and the dynamically generated musical compositions when they accurately match their current emotions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative tools similar to those used in LLMs and diffusion models like Midjourney and DALL-E have been used to generate in-game environments, and companies like Ubisoft have stated that they are experimenting with using AI to generate basic dialogue.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers at Roblox are using AI to generate 3D objects for players dubbed Cube 3D, an open-source AI that generates 3D objects based on the methods of LLMs to generate words.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI often amounts to pathfinding and finite-state machines.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding gets the AI from point A to point B, usually in the most direct way possible.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] State machines permit transitioning between different behaviors.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Monte Carlo tree search method provides a more engaging game experience by creating additional obstacles for the player to overcome.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The MCTS consists of a tree diagram in which the AI essentially plays tic-tac-toe.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Depending on the outcome, it selects a pathway yielding the next obstacle for the player.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In complex video games, these trees may have more branches, provided that the player can come up with several strategies to surpass the obstacle.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academic AI may play a role within game AI, outside the traditional concern of controlling NPC behavior.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural-content generation: Creating elements of the game environment like environmental conditions, levels, and even music in an automated way.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI methods can generate new content or interactive stories.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Data mining on user behavior: This allows game designers to explore how people use the game, what parts they play most, and what causes them to stop playing, allowing developers to tune gameplay or improve monetization.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Alternate approaches to NPCs: These include changing the game set-up to enhance NPC believability and exploring social rather than individual NPC behavior.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than procedural generation, some researchers have used generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create new content.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2018 researchers at Cornwall University trained a GAN on a thousand human-created levels for *Doom*; following training, the neural net prototype was able to design new playable levels on its own.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Similarly, researchers at the University of California prototyped a GAN to generate levels for Super Mario.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2020 Nvidia displayed a GAN-created clone of *Pac-Man*; the GAN learned how to recreate the game by watching 50,000 (mostly bot-generated) playthroughs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Non-player characters are entities within video games that are not controlled by players, but instead are managed by AI systems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs contribute to the immersion, storytelling, and the mechanics of a game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They often serve as companions, quest-givers, merchants and much more.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Their realism has advanced significantly in the past few years, thanks to improvements in AI technologies.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs are essential in both narrative-driven as well as open-world games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They help convey the lore and context of the game, making them pivotal to world-building and narrative progression.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, an NPC can provide critical information, offer quests, or simply populate the world to add a sense of realism to the game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, their role as quest-givers or merchants makes them integral to the gameplay loop, giving players access to resources, missions, or services that enable further progression.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, NPCs can be designed to serve functional roles in games, such as a merchant or to provide a service to the player.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These characters are central to facilitating game mechanics by acting as intermediaries between the player and in-game systems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academics say the interactions between players and NPCs are often designed to be straightforward but contextually relevant, ensuring that the player receives necessary feedback or resources for gameplay continuity.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in artificial intelligence have significantly enhanced the complexity and realism of NPCs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before these advancements, AI operated on pre-programmed behaviors, making them predictable and repeatable.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With AI developing NPCs have become more adaptive and able to dynamically respond to players.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts think the integration of deep learning and reinforcement learning techniques has enabled NPCs to adjust their behavior in response to player actions, creating a more interactive and personalized gameplay experience.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such development is the use of adaptive behavior models.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These allow NPCs to analyze and learn from players decisions in real time.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This behavior allows for a much more engaging experience.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example as said by experts in the field, NPCs in modern video games can now react to player actions with increased sophistication, such as adjusting their tactics in combat or changing their dialogue based on past interactions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] By using deep learning algorithms these systems emulate human-like decisions-making, thus making NPCs feel more like real people rather than static game elements.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another advancements in NPC AI is the use of natural language processing, which allows NPCs to engage in more realistic conversations with players.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before this NPC dialogue was limited to a fixed set of responses.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It is said that NLP has improved the fluidity of NPC conversations, allowing them to respond more contextually to player inputs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This development has increased the depth and immersion of player-NPC interactions, as players can now engage in more complex dialogues that affect the storyline and gameplay outcomes.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, deep learning models have allowed NPCs to become more capable of predicting players behaviors.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Deep learning allows NPCs to process large amounts of data and adapt to player strategies, making interactions with them less predictable and more varied.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This creates a more immersive experience, as NPCs are now able to "learn" from player behavior, which provides a greater sense of realism within the game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have led to more complex and adaptive behaviors in non-playable characters (NPCs).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, AI systems now utilize sophisticated techniques such as decision trees and state machines to enhance NPC interactions and realism, as discussed in "Artificial Intelligence in Games".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have also focused on improving dynamic and adaptive behaviors in NPCs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, recent research has explored the use of complex neural networks to enable NPCs to learn and adapt their behavior based on player actions, enhancing the overall gaming experience.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This approach is detailed in the IEEE paper on "AI Techniques for Interactive Game Systems".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite all of these advancements in NPC AI, there are still significant challenges that developers face in designing NPCs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They need to balance realism, functionally, and players expectations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The key challenge is to make sure that NPCs enhance the players experience, rather than disturb the gameplay.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Overly realistic NPCs that behave unpredictably can frustrate players by hindering progression or breaking immersion.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Conversely, NPCs that are too predictable or simplistic may fail to engage players, reducing the overall effectiveness of the game's narrative and mechanics.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another factor that needs to be accounted for is the computation cost of implementing advanced AI for NPCs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of these Advanced AI techniques requires large amount of processing power, which can limit its usage.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Balancing the performance of AI-driven NPCs with the game's overall technical limitations is crucial for ensuring smooth gameplay.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts mentioned how developers must allocate resources efficiently to avoid overburdening the game's systems, particularly in large, open-world games where numerous NPCs must interact with the player simultaneously.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Finally, creating NPCs that can respond dynamically to a wide range of player behaviors remains a difficult task.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs must be able to handle both scripted interactions and unscripted scenarios where players may behave in unexpected ways.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Designing NPCs capable of adapting to such variability requires complex AI models that can account for numerous possible interactions, which can be resource-intensive and time-consuming for developers.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the context of artificial intelligence in video games, cheating refers to the programmer giving agents actions and access to information that would be unavailable to the player in the same situation.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Believing that the Atari 8-bit could not compete against a human player, Chris Crawford did not fix a bug in *Eastern Front (1941)* that benefited the computer-controlled Russian side.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Computer Gaming World* in 1994 reported that "It is a well-known fact that many AIs 'cheat' (or, at least, 'fudge') in order to be able to keep up with human players".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the agents want to know if the player is nearby they can either be given complex, human-like sensors (seeing, hearing, etc.), or they can cheat by simply asking the game engine for the player's position.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Common variations include giving AIs higher speeds in racing games to catch up to the player or spawning them in advantageous positions in first-person shooters.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of cheating in AI shows the limitations of the "intelligence" achievable artificially; generally speaking, in games where strategic creativity is important, humans could easily beat the AI after a minimum of trial and error if it were not for this advantage.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheating is often implemented for performance reasons where in many cases it may be considered acceptable as long as the effect is not obvious to the player.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While cheating refers only to privileges given specifically to the AI—it does not include the inhuman swiftness and precision natural to a computer—a player might call the computer's inherent advantages "cheating" if they result in the agent acting unlike a human player.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sid Meier stated that he omitted multiplayer alliances in *Civilization* because he found that the computer was almost as good as humans in using them, which caused players to think that the computer was cheating.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers say that most game AIs are honest but they dislike players erroneously complaining about "cheating" AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, humans use tactics against computers that they would not against other people.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In short, cheating AI is when the game seems to break its own rules, producing impossible outcomes.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The opposite is dynamic difficulty, a structured adjustment of AI skill to maintain competition, respecting game mechanics.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some games may have a blend of both of these systems at once.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 1996 game *Creatures*, the user "hatches" small furry animals and teaches them how to behave.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These "Norns" can talk, feed themselves, and protect themselves against vicious creatures.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It was the first popular application of machine learning in an interactive simulation.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Neural networks are used by the creatures to learn what to do.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The game is regarded as a breakthrough in artificial life research, which aims to model the behavior of creatures interacting with their environment.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 2001 first-person shooter *Halo: Combat Evolved* the player assumes the role of the Master Chief, battling various aliens on foot or in vehicles.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemies use cover very wisely, and employ suppressing fire and grenades.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The squad situation affects the individuals, so certain enemies flee when their leader dies.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Attention is paid to the little details, with enemies notably throwing back grenades or team-members responding to being bothered.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The underlying "behavior tree" technology has become very popular in the games industry since *Halo 2*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2005 psychological horror first-person shooter *F.E.A.R.* has player characters engage a battalion of cloned super-soldiers, robots and paranormal creatures.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI uses a planner to generate context-sensitive behaviors, the first time in a mainstream game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This technology is still used as a reference for many studios.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Replicas are capable of utilizing the game environment to their advantage, such as overturning tables and shelves to create cover, opening doors, crashing through windows, or even noticing (and alerting the rest of their comrades to) the player's flashlight.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, the AI is also capable of performing flanking maneuvers, using suppressing fire, throwing grenades to flush the player out of cover, and even playing dead.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Most of these actions, in particular the flanking, is the result of emergent behavior.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The survival horror series *S.T.A.L.K.E.R.* (2007–) confronts the player with man-made experiments, military soldiers, and mercenaries known as Stalkers.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The various encountered enemies (if the difficulty level is set to its highest) use combat tactics and behaviors such as healing wounded allies, giving orders, out-flanking the player and using weapons with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2010 real-time strategy game *StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty* gives the player control of one of three factions in a 1v1, 2v2, or 3v3 battle arena.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The player must defeat their opponents by destroying all their units and bases.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is accomplished by creating units that are effective at countering opponents' units.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players can play against multiple different levels of AI difficulty ranging from very easy to Cheater 3 (insane).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI is able to cheat at the difficulty Cheater 1 (vision), where it can see units and bases when a player in the same situation could not.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheater 2 gives the AI extra resources, while Cheater 3 gives an extensive advantage over its opponent.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence, AI systems that can respond to prompts and produce text, images, and audio and video clips, arose in 2023 with systems like ChatGPT and Stable Diffusion.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In video games, these systems could create the potential for game assets to be created indefinitely, bypassing typical limitations on human creations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, the 2024 browser-based sandbox game *Infinite Craft* uses generative AI software, including LLaMA.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] When two elements are being combined, a new element is generated by the AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2024 browser-based game *Oasis* uses generative AI to simulate the video game *Minecraft*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* is trained on millions of hours of footage from *Minecraft*, and predicts how the next frame of gameplay looks using this dataset.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* does not have object permanence because it does not store any data.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2025 video game *AI2U: With You 'Til The End*, developed by AlterStaff Inc., used ChatGPT for the non-playable characters dialogue in the game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence has been included to perform video upscaling of game images.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Both NVidia's Deep Learning Super Sampling (DLSS) and AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution (FSR) have included AI as part of their engine.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In March 2026, NVidia announced version 5.0 of DLSS to release later in 2026, which among other improvements, includes an AI engine that "infuses pixels with photoreal lighting and materials" as to make existing game graphics appear more realistic.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NVidia's Jensen Huang said that developers will far more control over how DLSS 5.0 would interact with their games, allowing the developer to tweak lighting and texture adjustments, and that NVidia was continuing to improve the technology before its release.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there are similar concerns in other fields particularly the potential for loss of jobs normally dedicated to the creation of these assets.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Voice actors were one of the first groups to express concern on generative AI use in video games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The North American actor's union SAG-AFTRA had finished a strike in 2023 against television and film production companies, with the strike concluded on new contract terms that gave actors strong control over whether their voices could be used to train generative AI engines.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Shortly afterward, the union agreed to a contract with AI company Replica Studios to allow union voices to be used to train AI and used in games, with the contract assuring pay and rights protections.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While the contract was agreed upon by a SAG-AFTRA committee, many members expressed criticism of the move, having not been told of it until it was completed and that the deal did not do enough to protect the actors.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The strike concluded by July 2025 with the affected publishers agreeing to a contract that gave actors stronger control of whether their voices could be used for AI.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] To assure such content was disclosed by game publishers and avoid potential copyright issues, Valve implemented new requirements for games on Steam that the use of pre-generated AI assets or live generation via generative AI must be disclosed on the storefront page.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sweeney criticized this move, as "it makes it much, much, much harder for a game developer to have a chance of success.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In known environments with available models, planning can be done offline.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Solutions can be found and evaluated prior to execution.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In dynamically unknown environments, the strategy often needs to be revised online.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Solutions usually resort to iterative trial and error processes commonly seen in artificial intelligence.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These include dynamic programming, reinforcement learning and combinatorial optimization.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Languages used to describe planning and scheduling are often called action languages.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The difficulty of planning is dependent on the simplifying assumptions employed.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Several classes of planning problems can be identified depending on the properties the problems have in several dimensions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Since the initial state is known unambiguously, and all actions are deterministic, the state of the world after any sequence of actions can be accurately predicted, and the question of observability is irrelevant for classical planning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Further, plans can be defined as sequences of actions, because it is always known in advance which actions will be needed.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] With nondeterministic actions or other events outside the control of the agent, the possible executions form a tree, and plans have to determine the appropriate actions for every node of the tree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] When full observability is replaced by partial observability, planning corresponds to a partially observable Markov decision process (POMDP).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] If there are more than one agent, we have multi-agent planning, which is closely related to game theory.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In AI planning, planners typically input a domain model (a description of a set of possible actions which model the domain) as well as the specific problem to be solved specified by the initial state and goal, in contrast to those in which there is no input domain specified.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Such planners are called "domain independent" to emphasize the fact that they can solve planning problems from a wide range of domains.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Typical examples of domains are block-stacking, logistics, workflow management, and robot task planning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Hence a single domain-independent planner can be used to solve planning problems in all these various domains.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] On the other hand, a route planner is typical of a domain-specific planner.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The most commonly used languages for representing planning domains and specific planning problems, such as STRIPS and PDDL for Classical Planning, are based on state variables.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Each possible state of the world is an assignment of values to the state variables, and actions determine how the values of the state variables change when that action is taken.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Since a set of state variables induce a state space that has a size that is exponential in the set, planning, similarly to many other computational problems, suffers from the curse of dimensionality and the combinatorial explosion.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An alternative language for describing planning problems is that of hierarchical task networks, in which a set of tasks is given, and each task can be either realized by a primitive action or decomposed into a set of other tasks.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This does not necessarily involve state variables, although in more realistic applications state variables simplify the description of task networks.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action model learning (sometimes abbreviated action learning) is an area of machine learning concerned with the creation and modification of a software agent's knowledge about the *effects* and *preconditions* of the *actions* that can be executed within its *environment*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This knowledge is usually represented in a logic-based action description language and used as input for automated planners.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Learning action models is important when goals change.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] When an agent acted for a while, it can use its accumulated knowledge about actions in the domain to make better decisions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Thus, learning action models differs from reinforcement learning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It enables reasoning about actions instead of expensive trials in the world.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action model learning is a form of inductive reasoning, where new knowledge is generated based on the agent's *observations*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The usual motivation for action model learning is the fact that manual specification of action models for planners is often a difficult, time-consuming, and error-prone task (especially in complex environments).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Temporal planning can be solved with methods similar to classical planning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The main difference is, because of the possibility of several, temporally overlapping actions with a duration being taken concurrently, that the definition of a state has to include information about the current absolute time and how far the execution of each active action has proceeded.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Further, in planning with rational or real time, the state space may be infinite, unlike in classical planning or planning with integer time.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Temporal planning is closely related to scheduling problems when uncertainty is involved and can also be understood in terms of timed automata.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The Simple Temporal Network with Uncertainty (STNU) is a scheduling problem which involves controllable actions, uncertain events and temporal constraints.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Dynamic Controllability for such problems is a type of scheduling which requires a temporal planning strategy to activate controllable actions reactively as uncertain events are observed so that all constraints are guaranteed to be satisfied.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Probabilistic planning can be solved with iterative methods such as value iteration and policy iteration, when the state space is sufficiently small.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] With partial observability, probabilistic planning is similarly solved with iterative methods, but using a representation of the value functions defined for the space of beliefs instead of states.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In artificial intelligence, preference-based planning is a form of automated planning and scheduling which focuses on producing plans that additionally satisfy as many user-specified preferences as possible.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] In many problem domains, a task can be accomplished by various sequences of actions (also known as plans).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These plans can vary in quality: there can be many ways to solve a problem, but preferred generally are ways more, e.g., cost-effective, quick, and safe.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Preference-based planners take these preferences into account when producing a plan for a given problem.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Examples of preference-based planning software include *PPLAN* and *HTNPlan-P* (preference-based hierarchical task network (HTN) planning).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Deterministic planning was introduced with the STRIPS planning system, which is a hierarchical planner.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Action names are ordered in a sequence and this is a plan for the robot.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Hierarchical planning can be compared with an automatic generated behavior tree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The disadvantage is, that a normal behavior tree is not so expressive like a computer program.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] That means, the notation of a behavior graph contains action commands, but no loops or if-then-statements.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Conditional planning overcomes the bottleneck and introduces an elaborated notation which is similar to a control flow, known from other programming languages like Pascal.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It is very similar to program synthesis, which means a planner generates sourcecode which can be executed by an interpreter.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An early example of a conditional planner is “Warplan-C” which was introduced in the mid 1970s.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] What is the difference between a normal sequence and a complicated plan, which contains if-then-statements?
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It has to do with uncertainty at runtime of a plan.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The idea is that a plan can react to sensor signals which are unknown for the planner.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The planner generates two choices in advance.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For example, if an object was detected, then action A is executed, if an object is missing, then action B is executed.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A major advantage of conditional planning is the ability to handle partial plans.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] An agent is not forced to plan everything from start to finish but can divide the problem into chunks.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] This helps to reduce the state space and solves much more complex problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] We speak of "contingent planning" when the environment is observable through sensors, which can be faulty.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] It is thus a situation where the planning agent acts under incomplete information.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For a contingent planning problem, a plan is no longer a sequence of actions but a decision tree because each step of the plan is represented by a set of states rather than a single perfectly observable state, as in the case of classical planning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The selected actions depend on the state of the system.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] For example, if it rains, the agent chooses to take the umbrella, and if it doesn't, they may choose not to take it.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Littman showed in 1998 that with branching actions, the planning problem becomes EXPTIME-complete.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A particular case of contiguous planning is represented by FOND problems - for "fully-observable and non-deterministic".
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] If the goal is specified in LTLf (linear time logic on finite trace) then the problem is always EXPTIME-complete and 2EXPTIME-complete if the goal is specified with LDLf.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Conformant planning is when the agent is uncertain about the state of the system, and it cannot make any observations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] The agent then has beliefs about the real world, but cannot verify them with sensing actions, for instance.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] These problems are solved by techniques similar to those of classical planning, but where the state space is exponential in the size of the problem, because of the uncertainty about the current state.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] A solution for a conformant planning problem is a sequence of actions.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/automated-planning-and-scheduling] Haslum and Jonsson have demonstrated that the problem of conformant planning is EXPSPACE-complete, and 2EXPTIME-complete when the initial situation is uncertain, and there is non-determinism in the actions outcomes.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] A **blackboard system** is an artificial intelligence approach based on the blackboard architectural model, where a common knowledge base, the "blackboard", is iteratively updated by a diverse group of specialist knowledge sources, starting with a problem specification and ending with a solution.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Each knowledge source updates the blackboard with a partial solution when its internal constraints match the blackboard state.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] In this way, the specialists work together to solve the problem.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The blackboard model was originally designed as a way to handle complex, ill-defined problems, where the solution is the sum of its parts.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The **blackboard**, a shared repository of problems, partial solutions, suggestions, and contributed information.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The blackboard can be thought of as a dynamic "library" of contributions to the current problem that have been recently "published" by other knowledge sources.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The **control shell**, which controls the flow of problem-solving activity in the system.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Just as the eager human specialists need a moderator to prevent them from trampling each other in a mad dash to grab the chalk, KSs need a mechanism to organize their use in the most effective and coherent fashion.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] In a blackboard system, this is provided by the control shell.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] A blackboard system is the central space in a multi-agent system.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] It's used for describing the world as a communication platform for agents.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] To realize a blackboard in a computer program, a machine readable notation is needed in which facts can be stored.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] One attempt in doing so is a SQL database, another option is the **Learnable Task Modeling Language (LTML)**.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The syntax of the LTML planning language is similar to PDDL, but adds extra features like control structures and OWL-S models.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] LTML was developed in 2007 as part of a much larger project called POIROT (Plan Order Induction by Reasoning from One Trial), which is a Learning from demonstrations framework for process mining.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] In POIROT, Plan traces and hypotheses are stored in the LTML syntax for creating semantic web services.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Here is a small example: A human user is executing a workflow in a computer game.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The user presses some buttons and interacts with the game engine.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] While the user interacts with the game, a plan trace is created.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] That means the user's actions are stored in a logfile.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The logfile gets transformed into a machine readable notation which is enriched by semantic attributes.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The result is a textfile in the LTML syntax which is put on the blackboard.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Agents (software programs in the blackboard system) are able to parse the LTML syntax.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] We start by discussing two well known early blackboard systems, BB1 and GBB, below and then discuss more recent implementations and applications.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The BB1 blackboard architecture was originally inspired by studies of how humans plan to perform multiple tasks in a trip, used task-planning as a simplified example of tactical planning for the Office of Naval Research.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] A key innovation of BB1 was that it applied this opportunistic planning model to its own control, using the same blackboard model of incremental, opportunistic, problem-solving that was applied to solve domain problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Meta-level reasoning with control knowledge sources could then monitor whether planning and problem-solving were proceeding as expected or stalled.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] If stalled, BB1 could switch from one strategy to another as conditions – such as the goals being considered or the time remaining – changed.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] BB1 was applied in multiple domains: construction site planning, inferring 3-D protein structures from X-ray crystallography, intelligent tutoring systems, and real-time patient monitoring.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] BB1 also allowed domain-general language frameworks to be designed for wide classes of problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] For example, the ACCORD language framework defined a particular approach to solving configuration problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] The problem-solving approach was to incrementally assemble a solution by adding objects and constraints, one at a time.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Actions in the ACCORD language framework appear as short English-like commands or sentences for specifying preferred actions, events to trigger KSes, preconditions to run a KS action, and obviation conditions to discard a KS action that is no longer relevant.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] GBB focused on efficiency, in contrast to BB1, which focused more on sophisticated reasoning and opportunistic planning.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] GBB improves efficiency by allowing blackboards to be multi-dimensional, where dimensions can be either ordered or not, and then by increasing the efficiency of pattern matching.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] GBB1, one of GBB's control shells implements BB1's style of control while adding efficiency improvements.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Other well-known of early academic blackboard systems are the Hearsay II speech recognition system and Douglas Hofstadter's Copycat and Numbo projects.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems are used routinely in many military C4ISTAR systems for detecting and tracking objects.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Another example of current use is in Game AI, where they are considered a standard AI tool to help with adding AI to video games.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Blackboard-like systems have been constructed within modern Bayesian machine learning settings, using agents to add and remove Bayesian network nodes.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] In these 'Bayesian Blackboard' systems, the heuristics can acquire more rigorous probabilistic meanings as proposal and acceptances in Metropolis Hastings sampling though the space of possible structures.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Conversely, using these mappings, existing Metropolis-Hastings samplers over structural spaces may now thus be viewed as forms of blackboard systems even when not named as such by the authors.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Such samplers are commonly found in musical transcription algorithms for example.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/blackboard-system] Blackboard systems have also been used to build large-scale intelligent systems for the annotation of media content, automating parts of traditional social science research.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] In artificial intelligence, **hierarchical task network (HTN) planning** is an approach to automated planning in which the dependency among actions can be given in the form of hierarchically structured networks.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] 3. goal tasks (goal state), which roughly corresponds to the goals of STRIPS, but are more general.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] A solution to an HTN problem is then an executable sequence of primitive tasks that can be obtained from the initial task network by decomposing compound tasks into their set of simpler tasks, and by inserting ordering constraints.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] A primitive task is an action that can be executed directly given the state in which it is executed supports its precondition.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] A compound task is a complex task composed of a partially ordered set of further tasks, which can either be primitive or abstract.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] A goal task is a task of satisfying a condition.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] The difference between primitive and other tasks is that the primitive actions can be directly executed.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] Compound and goal tasks both require a sequence of primitive actions to be performed; however, goal tasks are specified in terms of conditions that have to be made true, while compound tasks can only be specified in terms of other tasks via the task network outlined below.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] Constraints among tasks are expressed in the form of networks, called (hierarchical) task networks.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] A task network is a set of tasks and constraints among them.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] Such a network can be used as the precondition for another compound or goal task to be feasible.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] This way, one can express that a given task is feasible only if a set of other actions (those mentioned in the network) are done, and they are done in such a way that the constraints among them (specified by the network) are satisfied.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] One particular formalism for representing hierarchical task networks that has been fairly widely used is TAEMS.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] HTN planning is strictly more expressive than STRIPS, to the point of being undecidable in the general case.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/hierarchical-task-network] However, many syntactic restrictions of HTN planning are decidable, with known complexities ranging from NP-complete to 2-EXPSPACE-complete, and some HTN problems can be efficiently compiled into PDDL, a STRIPS-like language.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] For example, consider navigating a mobile robot inside a building to a distant waypoint.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] It should execute this task while avoiding walls and not falling down stairs.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A motion planning algorithm would take a description of these tasks as input, and produce the speed and turning commands sent to the robot's wheels.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Motion planning algorithms might address robots with a larger number of joints (e.g., industrial manipulators), more complex tasks (e.g. manipulation of objects), different constraints (e.g., a car that can only drive forward), and uncertainty (e.g. imperfect models of the environment or robot).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The robot and obstacle geometry is described in a 2D or 3D *workspace*, while the motion is represented as a path in (possibly higher-dimensional) configuration space.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A configuration describes the pose of the robot, and the configuration space C is the set of all possible configurations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The set of configurations that avoids collision with obstacles is called the free space Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The complement of Cfree in C is called the obstacle or forbidden region.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Often, it is prohibitively difficult to explicitly compute the shape of Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] However, testing whether a given configuration is in Cfree is efficient.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] First, forward kinematics determine the position of the robot's geometry, and collision detection tests if the robot's geometry collides with the environment's geometry.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Target space is a subspace of free space which denotes where we want the robot to move to.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] In global motion planning, target space is observable by the robot's sensors.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] However, in local motion planning, the robot cannot observe the target space in some states.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] To solve this problem, the robot goes through several virtual target spaces, each of which is located within the observable area (around the robot).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A virtual target space is called a sub-goal.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Obstacle space is a space that the robot can not move to.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Obstacle space is not opposite of free space.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Low-dimensional problems can be solved with grid-based algorithms that overlay a grid on top of configuration space, or geometric algorithms that compute the shape and connectivity of Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Exact motion planning for high-dimensional systems under complex constraints is computationally intractable.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Potential-field algorithms are efficient, but fall prey to local minima (an exception is the harmonic potential fields).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms avoid the problem of local minima, and solve many problems quite quickly.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] They are unable to determine that no path exists, but they have a probability of failure that decreases to zero as more time is spent.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within Cfree (this is tested with collision detection).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] This discretizes the set of actions, and search algorithms (like A*) are used to find a path from the start to the goal.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] These approaches require setting a grid resolution.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Search is faster with coarser grids, but the algorithm will fail to find paths through narrow portions of Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Furthermore, the number of points on the grid grows exponentially in the configuration space dimension, which make them inappropriate for high-dimensional problems.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Traditional grid-based approaches produce paths whose heading changes are constrained to multiples of a given base angle, often resulting in suboptimal paths.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Any-angle path planning approaches find shorter paths by propagating information along grid edges (to search fast) without constraining their paths to grid edges (to find short paths).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches often need to search repeatedly, for example, when the knowledge of the robot about the configuration space changes or the configuration space itself changes during path following.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Incremental heuristic search algorithms replan fast by using experience with the previous similar path-planning problems to speed up their search for the current one.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] These approaches are similar to grid-based search approaches except that they generate a paving covering entirely the configuration space instead of a grid.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The paving is decomposed into two subpavings X−,X+ made with boxes such that X− ⊂ Cfree ⊂ X+.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Characterizing Cfree amounts to solve a set inversion problem.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Interval analysis could thus be used when Cfree cannot be described by linear inequalities in order to have a guaranteed enclosure.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The robot is thus allowed to move freely in X−, and cannot go outside X+.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] To both subpavings, a neighbor graph is built and paths can be found using algorithms such as Dijkstra or A*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] When a path is feasible in X−, it is also feasible in Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] When no path exists in X+ from one initial configuration to the goal, we have the guarantee that no feasible path exists in Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] As for the grid-based approach, the interval approach is inappropriate for high-dimensional problems, due to the fact that the number of boxes to be generated grows exponentially with respect to the dimension of configuration space.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] An illustration is provided by the three figures on the right where a hook with two degrees of freedom has to move from the left to the right, avoiding two horizontal small segments.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Nicolas Delanoue has shown that the decomposition with subpavings using interval analysis also makes it possible to characterize the topology of Cfree such as counting its number of connected components.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Given a bundle of rays around the current position attributed with their length hitting a wall, the robot moves into the direction of the longest ray unless a door is identified.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Such an algorithm was used for modeling emergency egress from buildings.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] One approach is to treat the robot's configuration as a point in a potential field that combines attraction to the goal, and repulsion from obstacles.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The resulting trajectory is output as the path.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] This approach has advantages in that the trajectory is produced with little computation.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] However, they can become trapped in local minima of the potential field and fail to find a path, or can find a non-optimal path.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The artificial potential fields can be treated as continuum equations similar to electrostatic potential fields (treating the robot like a point charge), or motion through the field can be discretized using a set of linguistic rules.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A navigation function or a probabilistic navigation function are sorts of artificial potential functions which have the quality of not having minimum points except the target point.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:goal-oriented-action-planning/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
